article.description: Candice Dupree has been on wrong side of this kind of rout, so she can readily identify with the struggles of the winless Atlanta Dream.
article.headline: Dupree drops in 20, grabs six boards as Sky cruise past Dream
article.linkText: Four score in double-digits as Sky stomp Dream
article.story:
CHICAGO -- Candice Dupree has been on wrong side of this kind of rout, so she can readily identify with the struggles of the winless Atlanta Dream.

Dupree scored 20 points, Jia Perkins had 19 and the third-year Chicago Sky cruised to a 91-70 victory over the expansion Dream on Saturday night.

"That was us two years ago and now we can laugh about it," Dupree said. "Obviously we can relate to losing games by 20-plus points and hopefully that won't ever happen to us [again]."

Dupree, who struggled with the Sky through a 5-29 rookie season in 2006, was among four Chicago players scoring in double figures as the team set a franchise record for margin of victory.

Chasity Melvin added 12 points and guard Cathy Joens had 10 to help the Sky (3-4) get their biggest win since an 18-point victory against Houston last year.

Chicago never trailed en route to winning its second straight -- a weekend home-and-home sweep of the Dream -- after a three-game losing streak. The Sky played once again without injured rookie Sylvia Fowles, who is out four to six weeks due to a sprained left knee.

Jennifer Lacy had 18 points and 10 rebounds to lead Atlanta (0-7), Betty Lennox had 17 and Ivory Latta 13.

Chicago used a 17-0 second quarter run to build a 52-26 halftime lead -- with the 26-point advantage also established a new mark for the third-year franchise.

The lead never dipped below 18 points in the second half.

Still, Atlanta coach Marynell Meadors was encouraged by her team's improved play after the break.

"We had zero points at halftime in the paint and we ended up with 28," Meadors said. "We didn't have any fast break points [at half] and we had seven in the second half. It was definitely encouraging and I thought we played extremely hard."

Chicago shot 54 percent (30-for-56) from the field and outrebounded Atlanta 35-24. Dupree, who also had six rebounds, shot 6-for-11 from the field and 8-for-10 from the free-throw line, and Perkins was 8-for-12 from the floor.
